2. Coagulation
Coagulation is the process of destabilising colloidal particles by neutralising their surface charge, allowing them
to come together. The term refers specifically to the chemical destabilisation step. Colloidal particles (1 nm – 1
μm) are stable because they carry a negative surface charge that causes electrostatic repulsion – preventing
aggregation.
2.1 Colloidal Stability and Zeta Potential
Colloidal Stability – The Electric Double Layer
Colloidal particles in water acquire a negative surface charge (usually from ionisation of surface groups or
preferential adsorption of anions).
This creates an Electric Double Layer:
• Stern layer: tightly bound counter-ions (cations) immediately adjacent to particle surface
• Diffuse layer: loosely bound ions extending into solution; gradually mixing with bulk
Zeta potential (z) = electrical potential at the shear plane (boundary between Stern layer and diffuse
layer)
High |z| (e.g., -30 mV) ® stable colloid (repels other particles)
Low |z| (near 0 mV) ® destabilised ® coagulation occurs
Coagulation aim: reduce z to near 0 mV by adding positively charged coagulant
