4.2 Slow Sand Filter (SSF) – Schmutzdecke
Schmutzdecke – The Biological Skin
The Schmutzdecke (German: "dirt skin") is a biologically active layer 1–5 cm thick that forms on the surface
of a slow sand filter. It consists of:
• Algae, bacteria, protozoa, rotifers, diatoms, fungi
• Organic matter and trapped particles
This layer provides: biological degradation of organics, predation of bacteria and pathogens, physical
straining of particles
Schmutzdecke takes 2–4 weeks to mature (ripening period). During this time, filter effluent quality is poor ® filtrate
must be recycled or wasted.
After scraping for cleaning, the schmutzdecke must re-mature again.
