5. pH – Concept, Scale and Environmental Significance
pH (potential of Hydrogen) is the negative logarithm (base 10) of the hydrogen ion activity in a solution. It is the
most frequently measured water quality parameter and controls virtually all chemical and biological processes in
aquatic environments. Introduced by Søren Sørensen in 1909.
5.1 Definition and pH Scale
pH Definition
pH = -lognn [Hn] (strictly: pH = -lognn {Hn} where {} = activity)
At 25°C: Kw = [Hn][OHn] = 10n¹n ® pH + pOH = 14
• Pure water: [Hn] = [OHn] = 10nn M ® pH = 7 (neutral)
• pH < 7: acidic ([Hn] > 10nn M)
• pH > 7: alkaline/basic ([OHn] > [Hn])
pH 6 = 10× more acidic than pH 7; pH 5 = 100× more acidic (log scale!)
