6. Redox Potential (Eh) – Oxidation–Reduction Potential
Redox potential (Eh), also called Oxidation–Reduction Potential (ORP), measures the tendency of a solution
to accept or donate electrons. It is as fundamental as pH in controlling the chemical speciation and fate of
elements in natural waters, soils, and sediments. Measured in millivolts (mV).
6.1 Basic Redox Concepts
Key Redox Definitions
Oxidation = loss of electrons (OIL: Oxidation Is Loss)
Reduction = gain of electrons (RIG: Reduction Is Gain)
Oxidising agent = electron acceptor (gets reduced); e.g., On, NOnn, Fe³n, SOn²n
Reducing agent = electron donor (gets oxidised); e.g., organic matter, Fe²n, HnS, NHnn
pe = negative log of electron activity = Eh × F/(2.303RT) At 25°C: pe = Eh(mV) / 59.2
High Eh (+): Oxidising conditions (On present; aerobic)
Low Eh (-): Reducing conditions (On absent; anaerobic)
6.2 The Nernst Equation
Nernst Equation
Eh = E° + (RT/nF) × ln([Ox]/[Red])
At 25°C simplified: Eh = E° + (0.0592/n) × log([Ox]/[Red])
Where:
E° = standard electrode potential (mV) at standard conditions (25°C, 1 atm, 1 M)
R = 8.314 J/mol·K; T = temperature (K); n = number of electrons transferred
F = Faraday constant = 96,485 C/mol
[Ox] = concentration of oxidised form; [Red] = concentration of reduced form
Example: Fe³n + en ® Fe²n; E° = +0.771 V Eh = 0.771 + 0.0592 × log([Fe³n]/[Fe²n])
6.3 Eh–pH Diagram (Pourbaix Diagram)
The Eh–pH diagram (Pourbaix diagram) maps the thermodynamically stable chemical species of an element as
a function of both Eh and pH. It is the single most powerful tool for predicting element speciation in natural
waters, soils, and sediments.
