6.6 Measurement of Eh
Eh is measured using a platinum electrode (inert; measures electron transfer) combined with a reference
electrode (e.g., Ag/AgCl, calomel). The measured potential is converted to Standard Hydrogen Electrode (SHE)
scale: Eh(SHE) = Eh(measured) + E(reference electrode). For Ag/AgCl reference: add +197 mV; for calomel:
add +242 mV. Measurement must be in situ or immediately after sampling (Eh changes rapidly on exposure to
air).
n EXAM TIP: Redox sequence (memorise order): On ® NOnn ® Mnnn ® Fe³n ® SOn²n ® COn
(decreasing Eh). High Eh = oxidising (aerobic); Low Eh = reducing (anaerobic). Nernst equation: Eh = E° +
(0.0592/n) × log([Ox]/[Red]) at 25°C. Eh–pH diagram = Pourbaix diagram. pe = Eh/59.2 at 25°C. Arsenic
crisis in Bangladesh: reducing groundwater ® As³n released from Fe oxides.
