4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: RO uses semi-permeable membranes with pore size < 0.001 μm under high pressure (15–80 bar) to
remove virtually all dissolved substances including monovalent ions (Nan, Cln). UF removes viruses and
macromolecules but NOT dissolved salts. Coagulation and SSF remove suspended/colloidal matter only.
Q6. At pH 4.5 in a lake, which of the following is most likely to occur?
(a) Maximum photosynthesis and algal bloom
(b) Al³n and Fe²n become soluble and toxic to fish
(c) CaCOn precipitation and water hardness increase
(d) Nitrification is enhanced
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: At pH 4.5 (strongly acidic): Al³n is soluble and directly toxic to fish gills. Fe²n (ferrous) is also mobilised.
Most fish cannot survive below pH 4.5. CaCOn precipitates at high pH (not acidic). Nitrification is severely inhibited
below pH 6.
Q7. In a reducing aquatic environment (Eh = -150 mV, pH 7), which form of iron predominates?
(a) Fe³n (ferric; insoluble)
(b) Fe²n (ferrous; soluble)
(c) FeSn (pyrite)
(d) Fe(OH)n precipitate
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: At Eh = -150 mV (reducing conditions), iron exists as Fe²n (ferrous ion) which is soluble. Fe³n is only
stable at higher Eh (oxidising conditions) where it precipitates as Fe(OH)n. This is why reducing groundwater often
has high dissolved iron – a common water quality problem in India.
Q8. Which electron acceptor is used by microorganisms IMMEDIATELY after dissolved oxygen is
depleted in a closed aquatic system?
(a) SOn²n (sulphate)
(b) COn (carbon dioxide)
(c) NOnn (nitrate)
(d) Fe³n (ferric iron)
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: The redox sequence from highest to lowest energy: On ® NOnn ® Mnnn ® Fe³n ® SOn²n ®
COn. Immediately after On is depleted, denitrifying bacteria use NOnn as the next most energetically favourable
electron acceptor. This is why wastewater treatment plants create anoxic zones for denitrification.
