8. Assertion–Reason Questions
Q1. [Assertion–Reason]
Assertion (A): Rapid sand filters require coagulation–flocculation as pre-treatment, but slow sand filters
do not.
Reason (R): Slow sand filters operate at lower rates and develop a biologically active Schmutzdecke
layer that removes particles and pathogens without prior chemical treatment.
(a) Both A and R true; R is correct explanation (b) Both true; R NOT correct explanation (c) A true, R false (d) A
false, R true
4 Answer: (a)
Explanation: Both A and R are true and R correctly explains A. SSF rate (0.1–0.4 m/hr) is so low that the
schmutzdecke has time to trap and biologically degrade particles. RSF operates at 4–12 m/hr – too fast for biological
action, so pre-coagulated flocs must be trapped. Select (a).
Q2. [Assertion–Reason]
Assertion (A): Ferric chloride is preferred over alum for coagulation of highly coloured, low-turbidity
water at low pH.
Reason (R): Ferric chloride forms Fe(OH)n floc which is effective only above pH 8.5.
(a) Both A and R true; R is correct explanation (b) Both true; R NOT correct explanation (c) A true, R false (d) A
false, R true
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: A is TRUE: FeCln works well at lower pH (4–6) and removes colour (humic acids) effectively; alum fails
below pH 6.5. R is FALSE: Fe(OH)n is effective over pH 4–11 (wide range), not just above pH 8.5. Select (c): A true,
R false.
Q3. [Assertion–Reason]
Assertion (A): In a waterlogged soil, arsenic contamination of groundwater is more severe.
Reason (R): Reducing conditions at low Eh cause Fe³n oxides to dissolve, releasing adsorbed Asnn
which is then reduced to more soluble and toxic As³n.
(a) Both A and R true; R is correct explanation (b) Both true; R NOT correct explanation (c) A true, R false (d) A
false, R true
4 Answer: (a)
Explanation: Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation. The classic Bangladesh/West Bengal arsenic
crisis follows this mechanism: flooding ® On depletion ® low Eh ® reductive dissolution of Fe(OH)n that had been
adsorbing As ® As released to groundwater, further reduced to As³n (arsenite; more toxic and soluble). Select (a).
Q4. [Assertion–Reason]
Assertion (A): Adding excess alum beyond the optimal dose can lead to restabilisation of colloidal
particles.
Reason (R): Excess Al³n ions and positive Al(OH)n surfaces provide excess positive charge, reversing
the zeta potential from negative through zero to positive, causing charge reversal and restabilisation.
(a) Both A and R true; R is correct explanation (b) Both true; R NOT correct explanation (c) A true, R false (d) A
false, R true
4 Answer: (a)
Explanation: Both A and R are true and R correctly explains the "zeta reversal" phenomenon. This is why the jar test
is so important – finding the optimal dose before the point of restabilisation. Over-dosing wastes coagulant AND
worsens water quality. Select (a).
